Navigation
moving around the system
1.pwd: remind yourself where you presently are .
2.ls : or ls [options] [location] ; we can get more details with the second form , 


3.path : get to a particular file or directory on the system.
type of phath are absolute (/)and relative path 
example:
absolute :
ls /home/ryan/Documents
relative  : 
ls Documents
they will get the same result 


path 
~ file name
. /file name
  ../../ (will go back )
4.cd 
note about cd ;If you run the command cd without any arguments then it will always take you back to your home directory


let's summrize 
pwd
Print Working Directory - ie. Where are we currently.
ls
List the contents of a directory.
cd
Change Directories - ie. move to another directory.
** Relative path
A file or directory location relative to where we currently are in the file system.
** Absolute path
A file or directory location in relation to the root of the file system.




